1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,650
Excusitis appears in a wide variety of forms, but the worst types of this disease are health excusitis,

2
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:13,650
intelligence excusitis, age excusitis, and luck excusitis.

3
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:19,011
Now let's see just how we can protect ourselves from these four common ailments.

4
00:00:19,011 --> 00:00:20,771
1.

5
00:00:21,040 --> 00:00:23,090
But my health isn't good.

6
00:00:23,760 --> 00:00:28,530
Health excusitis ranges all the way from the chronic, I don't feel good,

7
00:00:28,640 --> 00:00:32,611
to the more specific, I've got such and such wrong with me.

8
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:40,451
Bad health, in a thousand different forms, is used as an excuse for failing to do what a person wants to do,

9
00:00:40,641 --> 00:00:47,491
failing to accept greater responsibilities, failing to make more money, failing to achieve success.

10
00:00:48,161 --> 00:00:52,690
Millions and millions of people suffer from health excusitis.

11
00:00:52,801 --> 00:00:56,291
But is it in most cases a legitimate excuse?

12
00:00:56,400 --> 00:01:01,171
Think for a moment of all the highly successful people you know who could,

13
00:01:01,280 --> 00:01:04,611
but who don't, use health as an excuse.

14
00:01:05,120 --> 00:01:11,570
My physician and surgeon friends tell me the perfect specimen of adult life is non-existent.

15
00:01:11,760 --> 00:01:14,690
There is something physically wrong with everybody.

16
00:01:15,041 --> 00:01:21,971
Many surrender in whole or in part to health excusitis, but success-thinking people do not.

17
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:30,370
Two experiences happened to me in one afternoon that illustrate the correct and incorrect attitudes toward health.

18
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:33,250
I had just finished a talk in Cleveland.

19
00:01:33,361 --> 00:01:39,171
Afterward, one fellow, about thirty, asked to speak to me privately for a few minutes.

20
00:01:39,361 --> 00:01:45,651
He complimented me on the meeting, but then said, I'm afraid your ideas can't do me much good.

21
00:01:46,161 --> 00:01:52,130
You see, he continued, I've got a bad heart, and I've got to hold myself in check.

22
00:01:52,481 --> 00:01:57,890
He went on to explain that he'd seen four doctors, but they couldn't find his trouble.

23
00:01:58,161 --> 00:02:01,010
He asked me what I would suggest he do.

24
00:02:01,681 --> 00:02:07,010
Well, I said, I know nothing about the heart, but as one layman to another,

25
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:09,411
here are three things I'd do.

26
00:02:09,681 --> 00:02:16,450
First, I'd visit the finest heart specialist I could find and accept his diagnosis as final.

27
00:02:16,721 --> 00:02:22,450
You've already checked with four doctors, and none of them has found anything peculiar with your heart.

28
00:02:22,640 --> 00:02:25,331
Let the fifth doctor be your final check.

29
00:02:25,601 --> 00:02:29,250
It may very well be you've got a perfectly sound heart.

30
00:02:29,440 --> 00:02:34,931
But if you keep on worrying about it, eventually you may have a very serious heart ailment.

31
00:02:35,281 --> 00:02:40,531
Looking and looking and looking for an illness often actually produces illness.

